{"id":"2005.10060","submitter":"Antti M\\\"akinen","authors":"Antti J. M\\\"akinen, Rasmus Zetter, Joonas Iivanainen, Koos C. J.\n  Zevenhoven, Lauri Parkkonen, Risto J. Ilmoniemi","title":"Magnetic-field modeling with surface currents: Physical and\n  computational principles of bfieldtools","comments":"Updated document style, some references and wordings. 15 pages, 8\n  figures","journal-ref":"Journal of Applied Physics 128, 063906 (2020)","doi":"10.1063/5.0016090","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph physics.app-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Surface currents provide a general way to model static magnetic fields in\nsource-free volumes. To facilitate the use of surface currents in\nmagneto-quasistatic problems, we have implemented a set of computational tools\nin a Python package named bfieldtools. In this work, we describe the physical\nand computational principles of this toolset. To be able to work with surface\ncurrents of arbitrary shape, we discretize the currents on triangle meshes\nusing piecewise-linear stream functions. We apply analytical discretizations of\nintegral equations to obtain the magnetic field and potentials associated with\nthe discrete stream function. In addition, we describe the computation of the\nspherical multipole expansion and a novel surface-harmonic expansion for\nsurface currents, both of which are useful for representing the magnetic field\nin source-free volumes with a small number of parameters. Last, we share\nexamples related to magnetic shielding and surface-coil design using the\npresented tools.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 May 2020 14:09:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 2 Jun 2020 08:25:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-17"}
